EMA is requesting more data from Janssen (J&J) for its vaccine that is already in use under EUA. Further reports on contaminated AstraZeneca vaccine charges found at the University of Ulm (Germany) cannot be explained completely by the manufacturer which refers to highest standards in production processes, however, the additional proteins found in the vaccine may relate to the production process. It raises some concerns about production process standards in Chinese manufacturing, and safety concerns will be doubled up. EMA will demand more info and data on both Sinovac and Sinopharm vaccines, even though the latter one is reportedly in the approval process already. Because trustworthiness is key to vaccination campaigns and reaching herd immunization, EMA has no room for failure, and will have zero tolerance for unclear dataand will not compromise. One or both of the Chinese vaccines may ultimately be authorized, but likely not before 01 September 2021.

I think most here are missing one point in how approval works. At least in Europe (but I think FDA is the same) you need to provide better results, either effectiveness or less side effects (or some combination thereof), than the current state of care. This is after you have proven safety (phase I & II trials). The reason why the few new vaccines pass stage three is that showing statistically better results is hard for things where effective vaccines already exist or, if non exists yet, there are very few cases and therefore the statistical significance is not reached in a reasonable amount of time (making it more likely to be a financial loss). For Covid on these two reasons are non-issues. At least for the first couple of vaccines. I'm not sure how this translates to later applications though and I don't think it is a relevant contribution to the resolution of this question.
